Approach 3: Monotonic Stack (Most Optimal)
Intuition

Instead of storing temperatures, store indices in a Monotonic Decreasing Stack.

For every current temperature:

If it is warmer than the temperature at the stack's top index,
then it is the answer for that index.
Pop the index and calculate the waiting days.
Push the current index.

Remaining indices have no warmer day, so their answer stays 0.

Algorithm
Traverse temperatures

↓

Current Temperature > Temperature at Stack Top

↓

Pop Index

↓

Store Waiting Days

↓

Push Current Index
Java (Your Code)
class Solution {
    public int[] dailyTemperatures(int[] temperatures) {

        int results[] = new int[temperatures.length];

        Stack<Integer> st = new Stack<>();

        for (int i = 0; i < temperatures.length; i++) {

            while (!st.isEmpty() &&
                   temperatures[st.peek()] < temperatures[i]) {

                results[st.peek()] = i - st.pop();
            }

            st.push(i);
        }

        return results;
    }
}

